    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-12T08:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-12T08:10:00-05:00" n="620"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d620">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.115 Panay/8: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander of the United States Yangtze Patrol</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marquart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of Naval Operations</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="50" xml:id="d620fn50">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Navy Department</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Above Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-12T21:10:00+08:00"
                            >December 12, 1937—9:10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 12—5:53 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>0012. <hi rend="italic">Panay</hi> endangered by artillery fire forced move
                    anchorage farther up river. British gunboats and foreign merchant vessels
                    between Wuhu and Nanking subjected direct artillery and air attacks throughout
                    day. H. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Ladybird</hi> struck four times by Japanese
                    shells at Wuhu, one seaman killed, several wounded. Situation Nanking uncertain
                    but Chinese apparently still hold city.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
